When a user exceeds their query limit the API returns an HTTP 429 (Too Many Requests) error and rate-limit information in the response. Example responses from the docs:

- Monthly limit exceeded:
{
  "success": false,
  "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
  "usage": {
    "current": 101,
    "max": 100,
    "exceeded": true,
    "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
  }
}

- Generic rate-limit response:
{
  "error": {
    "code": "RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED",
    "message": "Rate limit exceeded. Try again in 60 seconds"
  }
}

You will also receive rate-limit headers on responses (for example X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset) indicating your window, remaining requests, and when the limit resets.

When a user exceeds their monthly query limit the API returns an error (HTTP 429 Too Many Requests) and includes rate-limit details. Typical response contents:

- HTTP status: 429 Too Many Requests
- Body example:
  {
    "success": false,
    "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
    "usage": {
      "current": 101,
      "max": 100,
      "exceeded": true,
      "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
    }
  }
- Alternate 429 form:
  {
    "error": {
      "code": "RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED",
      "message": "Rate limit exceeded. Try again in 60 seconds"
    }
  }
- Rate-limit headers are also returned (e.g. X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset or a reset_at timestamp).

Requests will continue to be rejected until the limit window resets (or you increase your quota).
